Let $f(n)$ be the number of ways to tile an $n\times 1$ board with red, blue, and green tiles such that all three colors are used at least once. We will use recursion to compute $f(n)$. We consider the rightmost tile in the tiling of the $n\times 1$ board. If it is a $1\times 1$ tile, then the remaining $n-1$ squares can be tiled in $f(n-1)$ ways. If it is a $2\times 1$ tile, then the remaining $n-2$ squares can be tiled in $f(n-2)$ ways. Therefore, we have the recursion $f(n)=f(n-1)+f(n-2)$ for $n\geq 3$, with initial conditions $f(1)=0$, $f(2)=0$, and $f(3)=6$. To see that $f(3)=6$, we can simply list out the possible tilings of a $3\times 1$ board using red, blue, and green tiles:

[asy]
size(80);
draw((0,0)--(7,0));
draw((0,-1)--(7,-1));
draw((0,-2)--(7,-2));
fill((0,0)--(1,0)--(1,-1)--(0,-1)--cycle,red);
fill((1,0)--(2,0)--(2,-1)--(1,-1)--cycle,blue);
fill((2,0)--(3,0)--(3,-1)--(2,-1)--cycle,green);
fill((3,0)--(4,0)--(4,-1)--(3,-1)--cycle,red);
fill((4,0)--(5,0)--(5,-1)--(4,-1)--cycle,green);
fill((5,0)--(6,0)--(6,-1)--(5,-1)--cycle,blue);
[/asy]

Thus, we can compute $f(4)=f(3)+f(2)=6+0=6$, $f(5)=f(4)+f(3)=6+6=12$, $f(6)=f(5)+f(4)=12+6=18$, $f(7)=f(6)+f(5)=18+12=30$. Therefore, the remainder when $N=f(7)$ is divided by $1000$ is $\boxed{030}$.
